<br>
The smallest rectangle is the &quot;safe image area,&quot;  drawn in a dotted line with little rectangles near the corners.  Nothing inside this block will be cut off or hidden by the spine of a book.  All important art and dialogue should go here.  In older comics, all panels whould be drawn inside this area, but these days &quot;full bleed&quot; pages are the norm.  Speaking of...<br>
<br>
The second rectangle is the crop border.  This is where, ideally, the edge of the image or a &quot;full bleed&quot; page should be.  Full bleed means the image goes right to the edge or the paper.  However, because mistakes can be made in printing or the page cropped incorrectly, there's a third line....<br>
<br>
This line has rulers on it to help with drawing panels, backgrounds, etc.  All art that you want to extend to the edge of the page should extend to this line to prevent white spaces at the edge of the art.<br>
<br>
The arrows around the ruled border help when measuring panels for traditional layouts (with 2x3, 2x4, 3x3, or 3x4 panels)  Full Bleed pages usually have irregular panel layouts so these don't really apply.  The arrows are 4mm apart on A4 paper, so I usually keep my borders to that size.<br>
<br>
Oh yeah, if your paper has japanese printing on it like mine, the lines at the bottom say &quot;title,&quot; &quot;name,&quot; and &quot;page.&quot;<br>
<br>
